We are given two problems intertwined. First, we compute \(k = \binom{20}{2} - 187 = 190 - 187 = 3\). Next, we find cubic polynomials \(p\) and \(q\) such that \(p(0) = -24\), \(q(0) = 30\), and \(p(q(x)) = q(p(x))\) for all real \(x\). Writing \(p(x) = a x^3 + b x^2 + c x - 24\) and \(q(x) = A x^3 + B x^2 + C x + 30\), the condition \(p(q(x)) = q(p(x))\) implies \(A = -a\) (since \(a \neq 0\) and \(A = a\) leads to a contradiction). Further, we derive \(b = -B\) and \(c = -C\). Using \(p(30) = q(-24)\) and equating the \(x^6\) coefficients in \(p(q(x))\) and \(q(p(x))\), we obtain \(b = -9a\) and \(c = 9 + 18a\). These relations yield a family of solutions parameterized by \(a \neq 0\). Computing \(p(3)\) and \(q(6)\) with \(k = 3\) gives \(p(3) = 27a + 9b + 3c - 24\) and \(q(6) = -216a - 36b - 6c + 30\). Substituting \(b = -9a\) and \(c = 9 + 18a\) simplifies both expressions to \(p(3) = 3\) and \(q(6) = -24\), independent of \(a\). Thus, the ordered pair is \((3, -24)\).

